---
import BaseLayout from '../layouts/BaseLayout.astro';
---

<BaseLayout
  title="Press | Ultra Zoom"
  description="Press kit, launch release, and media contact for Ultra Zoom, the privacy-respecting hover-to-zoom browser extension from Lost Rabbit Digital LLC."
  currentPage="press"
  og={{
    url: 'https://ultrazoom.app/press',
    title: 'Ultra Zoom Press Kit',
    description: 'Releases, boilerplate, quick facts, and media contact for Ultra Zoom.',
    image: 'https://ultrazoom.app/og/press.png',
    imageWidth: 1200,
    imageHeight: 630,
  }}
>
    <main class="main page-content" id="main-content">
        <h1>Press</h1>

        <p class="pricing-intro">
            Ultra Zoom is a hover-to-zoom browser extension built by Lost Rabbit Digital LLC.
            This page mirrors the official releases and collects everything a journalist
            or reviewer needs in one place. For interview requests, demo accounts, or
            higher-resolution screenshots, contact <a href="mailto:boden@lostrabbitdigital.com">boden@lostrabbitdigital.com</a>.
        </p>

        <section class="help-section" id="release-ai-upscaling">
            <h2>Latest release</h2>

            <article class="press-release">
                <p class="press-meta"><strong>FOR IMMEDIATE RELEASE</strong></p>

                <h3 class="press-headline">Ultra Zoom Adds On-Device AI Upscaling and Listing-Aware Overlays for Real-Estate Pros</h3>
                <p class="press-subhead">Privacy-first hover-to-zoom extension ships a locally bundled Real-ESRGAN model, Redfin/Zillow/Realtor.com listing captions, and a free tier that absorbs features once gated behind Pro.</p>

                <p>
                    <strong>May 5, 2026</strong> &mdash; Lost Rabbit Digital LLC today announced
                    a major update to Ultra Zoom, its hover-to-zoom browser extension for
                    Google Chrome and Mozilla Firefox. The release introduces on-device AI
                    upscaling, listing-aware overlays for real-estate sites, and a rebalanced
                    free tier that opens up several features previously reserved for paying
                    subscribers.
                </p>

                <h4 class="press-section-heading">AI image upscaling that never leaves the browser</h4>
                <p>
                    Ultra Zoom now reconstructs detail in low-resolution images at hover time
                    using <strong>Real-ESRGAN (general x4v3)</strong>, a neural upscaling model
                    that runs entirely on the user&rsquo;s device. The model weights ship inside
                    the extension package itself &mdash; there is no remote inference endpoint,
                    no cloud GPU dependency, and no opt-in for cross-network image transmission
                    because no image data is ever sent off the machine. When the model can&rsquo;t
                    initialize on a particular device, Ultra Zoom falls back to high-quality
                    Lanczos resampling automatically.
                </p>
                <p>
                    The feature is targeted at workflows where users routinely encounter
                    aggressively compressed images they need to inspect: MLS listing photos,
                    e-commerce product thumbnails, archival scans, and auction-catalog
                    imagery. Users can toggle AI upscaling on a per-domain basis from the
                    extension popup.
                </p>

                <blockquote class="press-quote">
                    &ldquo;Most AI features in browser extensions today work by uploading
                    your data to a third-party server. We refused to ship that. The model
                    is bundled with Ultra Zoom, runs locally on your CPU or GPU, and the
                    image you&rsquo;re hovering over never leaves the browser. That&rsquo;s
                    the only architecture that&rsquo;s consistent with the privacy promise
                    we made at launch.&rdquo;
                    <cite>&mdash; David McHale, founder, Lost Rabbit Digital</cite>
                </blockquote>

                <h4 class="press-section-heading">Listing-aware overlays for buyer agents and brokers</h4>
                <p>
                    Ultra Zoom&rsquo;s plugins for <strong>Redfin, Zillow, Realtor.com,
                    and Crexi</strong> now extract structured listing data alongside the
                    photo. The hover overlay surfaces the listing&rsquo;s status (NEW, OPEN,
                    SOLD), price, full address, and the beds / baths / square-footage
                    line as a caption. A new <code>Shift+L</code> shortcut opens the
                    underlying listing page; <code>A</code> copies the address to the
                    clipboard.
                </p>
                <p>
                    On Redfin, the gallery enumeration logic now resolves <em>every</em>
                    photo in a listing rather than only the thumbnails rendered in the
                    page DOM, so a buyer&rsquo;s agent can arrow-key through a 40-photo
                    listing without leaving the search-results view. Theater mode &mdash;
                    which expands the active overlay to fill the browser window &mdash;
                    no longer clips scroll-zoom past the original image bounds, removing
                    a long-standing rough edge in detail-page review. A separate
                    commercial-real-estate bundle covers Crexi listings for industrial,
                    retail, multifamily, and office workflows.
                </p>

                <h4 class="press-section-heading">Free-tier expansion: democratizing premium features</h4>
                <p>
                    Several capabilities that previously required a Pro subscription
                    are now available to all users, with Ultra Zoom attribution applied
                    where the image leaves the browser:
                </p>
                <ul class="help-list">
                    <li><strong>Region copy</strong> (<code>Shift+C</code>) and <strong>batch download</strong> (<code>Shift+D</code>, up to five images per session) ship to free users with a small attribution watermark composited into each export. Pro removes both the watermark and the cap.</li>
                    <li>The <strong>EXIF panel</strong> (<code>I</code>), the <strong>color-palette tool</strong> (<code>P</code>), and a <strong>windowed gallery filmstrip</strong> are now free for everyone. Pro adds JSON / CSS / GPX export from those panels.</li>
                    <li>A new <code>K</code> shortcut toggles the listing-detail caption strip on demand without changing the global setting.</li>
                </ul>
                <p>
                    The change reflects feedback from buyer agents, researchers, and
                    archivists who were hitting paywalls in the middle of routine
                    workflows. &ldquo;The free tier should feel useful, not crippled,&rdquo;
                    McHale said. &ldquo;Pro is for people who want export power and no
                    branding on their captures &mdash; it&rsquo;s not a tax on basic
                    review.&rdquo;
                </p>

                <h4 class="press-section-heading">Availability</h4>
                <p>
                    The update is rolling out now via the
                    <a href="https://chromewebstore.google.com/detail/ultra-zoom/jalclpdejbeamaamcpbolkclpnleagmg" target="_blank" rel="noopener">Chrome Web Store</a>
                    and the
                    <a href="https://addons.mozilla.org/en-US/firefox/addon/ultra-zoom/" target="_blank" rel="noopener">Firefox Add-ons gallery</a>.
                    Existing installations will receive it automatically through their
                    browser&rsquo;s extension update channel. Documentation, release notes,
                    and the full list of supported sites are published at
                    <a href="https://ultrazoom.app">https://ultrazoom.app</a>.
                </p>
            </article>
        </section>

        <section class="help-section" id="release">
            <h2>Launch release</h2>

            <article class="press-release">
                <p class="press-meta"><strong>FOR IMMEDIATE RELEASE</strong></p>

                <h3 class="press-headline">Ultra Zoom Launches Hover-to-Zoom Browser Extension Built Without Tracking</h3>
                <p class="press-subhead">Independent studio releases a Chrome and Firefox add-on that restores hover-to-zoom on image-heavy websites without collecting browsing data.</p>

                <p>
                    <strong>April 2, 2026</strong> &mdash; Lost Rabbit Digital LLC today announced the public launch of
                    Ultra Zoom, a free hover-to-zoom browser extension for Google Chrome and Mozilla Firefox.
                    The tool enlarges any image on a webpage the moment a cursor passes over it, replacing
                    a workflow that has long required users to open photos in separate tabs.
                </p>

                <p>
                    Hover-to-zoom is a long-standing browser feature category, but the most widely installed
                    extensions in the space have a troubled history. The original Hover Zoom extension, once
                    installed by millions of users, was caught logging the URLs of every page its users
                    visited and selling the data. Successor extensions have stopped working on the
                    highest-traffic image sites, including major image search engines, social networks, and
                    marketplace platforms.
                </p>

                <p>
                    Ultra Zoom is engineered to make that scenario structurally impossible, the company said.
                    The extension contains no analytics endpoints, no remote-code loaders, and no server-side
                    component that processes browsing activity. All image handling happens in the browser.
                    The codebase is built on Manifest V3, the current Chrome extension security standard,
                    which restricts the dynamic code patterns that enabled past privacy abuses.
                </p>

                <blockquote class="press-quote">
                    &ldquo;People shouldn&rsquo;t have to choose between a tool that works and a tool that
                    respects them. Ultra Zoom does the boring thing: it zooms images, and that&rsquo;s it.
                    There is no telemetry pipeline because we never built one. There is no opt-out for data
                    collection because there is no data collection.&rdquo;
                    <cite>&mdash; David McHale, founder, Lost Rabbit Digital</cite>
                </blockquote>

                <p>
                    The extension supports more than sixty popular destinations out of the box, including
                    Google Images, Bing Images, Instagram, Pinterest, Reddit, Amazon, eBay, AliExpress,
                    Unsplash, Pexels, Wikimedia Commons, Getty, AP News, and Bilibili. A generic engine
                    handles hover-zoom on the long tail of websites that do not have a dedicated plugin,
                    and a community-maintained URL rules pack lets users add new sites between releases. Pro subscribers on monthly billing receive pack updates as they ship.
                </p>

                <p>
                    Free features include theater mode, which expands a hovered image to fill the browser
                    window; one-key reverse image search shortcuts for Google, TinEye, Yandex, and other
                    engines; gallery navigation with arrow keys; and a local hover history of the last fifty
                    images a user has previewed. Power features such as video playback controls, batch image
                    download, an expanded one-thousand-entry hover history with full-text search, and custom
                    URL rules are bundled in an optional Pro tier priced at $3.99 per month, $29.99 per year, or $59.99 for a
                    lifetime license. A seven-day free trial is available at install.
                </p>

                <p>
                    Ultra Zoom is available immediately from the
                    <a href="https://chromewebstore.google.com/detail/ultra-zoom/jalclpdejbeamaamcpbolkclpnleagmg" target="_blank" rel="noopener">Chrome Web Store</a>
                    and the
                    <a href="https://addons.mozilla.org/en-US/firefox/addon/ultra-zoom/" target="_blank" rel="noopener">Firefox Add-ons gallery</a>.
                    Install links, documentation, and the full list of supported sites are published at
                    <a href="https://ultrazoom.app">https://ultrazoom.app</a>.
                </p>
            </article>
        </section>

        <section class="help-section" id="quick-facts">
            <h2>Quick facts</h2>
            <ul class="help-list">
                <li><strong>Product:</strong> Ultra Zoom &mdash; hover-to-zoom browser extension.</li>
                <li><strong>Publisher:</strong> Lost Rabbit Digital LLC, an independent, bootstrapped software studio.</li>
                <li><strong>Founder:</strong> David McHale.</li>
                <li><strong>Browsers:</strong> Google Chrome (Manifest V3) and Mozilla Firefox.</li>
                <li><strong>Pricing:</strong> Free core extension. Optional Ultra Zoom Pro at $3.99 / month, $29.99 / year, or $59.99 lifetime, with a 7-day free trial.</li>
                <li><strong>Privacy posture:</strong> Zero telemetry, zero analytics, no remote code, no server-side processing of browsing data &mdash; including AI features.</li>
                <li><strong>AI upscaling:</strong> Real-ESRGAN (general x4v3) bundled with the extension and run locally; Lanczos fallback. No image data is transmitted.</li>
                <li><strong>Coverage:</strong> 60+ optimized site plugins plus a generic engine and a community URL rules pack. Listing-aware overlays for Redfin, Zillow, Realtor.com, and Crexi.</li>
                <li><strong>Launched:</strong> April 2, 2026. Most recent major update: May 5, 2026.</li>
            </ul>
        </section>

